<DocsLayout title="Project 9: The Scaled System" description="Build an online ordering platform for organic produce with auto-scaling, CDN, Terraform modules, and cost monitoring.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 9: The Scaled System</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can architect and operate a system that scales automatically under load and recovers from failure."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">An online ordering platform for FreshBox — Emma's organic produce delivery service across Melbourne's inner suburbs. Weekly box subscriptions, one-time orders, delivery scheduling by suburb (different delivery days for different suburbs), real-time stock management (produce is perishable — stock levels change throughout the day as items sell out or arrive from farms). Customer accounts with order history.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Auto-scaling, CDN, and cost as a design constraint. Until now, your infrastructure was fixed — a set number of instances handling a predictable load. This project changes that. An Auto Scaling Group adjusts capacity based on demand. CloudFront caches static assets and API responses at edge locations worldwide. Terraform modules organise your infrastructure into reusable, composable units. And for the first time, you estimate costs before deploying and monitor spend after.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You also write Architecture Decision Records (ADRs) — formal documents recording why you chose one approach over another. The decisions you've been making informally since Project 6 now get written down.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Production systems don't run at constant load. Traffic spikes. Marketing campaigns drive surges. A TV feature can 10x your orders overnight. Auto-scaling handles this automatically — adding instances when demand rises, removing them when it falls. CloudFront reduces load on your backend by serving cached responses from edge locations. And cost monitoring ensures you don't get a surprise AWS bill. These are the tools that separate "it works" from "it works in production."</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "Auto Scaling Group scales out when CPU exceeds 70% or requests exceed 1,000/min, scales in when load drops",
    "CloudFront serves static assets from edge locations and caches API responses with short TTL",
    "Terraform infrastructure is organised into reusable modules (VPC, compute, database, CDN)",
    "k6 load test proves the system handles 100 concurrent users without inventory overselling",
    "Race condition test: 10 simultaneous requests for the last item — only one succeeds",
    "AWS Budget alarm triggers at $100/month spend",
    "Emma can manage inventory, view orders, and schedule deliveries by suburb",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Configure EC2 Auto Scaling Groups with scaling policies</li>
    <li>Set up CloudFront CDN for static assets and API caching</li>
    <li>Organise Terraform into reusable modules with inputs and outputs</li>
    <li>Handle race conditions with database-level locking or optimistic concurrency</li>
    <li>Load test with k6 and verify scaling behaviour</li>
    <li>Estimate and monitor AWS costs (Cost Explorer, Budgets, Infracost)</li>
    <li>Write Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)</li>
    <li>Plan capacity from client growth projections</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Tech stack</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>React + FastAPI + RDS PostgreSQL (multi-AZ)</li>
    <li>EC2 Auto Scaling Group behind ALB</li>
    <li>CloudFront for static assets and API caching</li>
    <li>S3 with lifecycle policies</li>
    <li>Terraform with modules</li>
    <li>Prometheus + Grafana for monitoring</li>
    <li>k6 for load testing</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/8">Project 8</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">3-4 weeks. The planning artifacts follow the established pattern. The new dimensions — auto-scaling, CDN configuration, Terraform modules, load testing, and cost monitoring — add significant infrastructure complexity. Minimal guidance from here — you own everything.</p>

